Q1: EDA Part 1 Individual Variables

Residential Area

Log scale is used here to better visualize the spread of a heavily right-skewed variable. Each step on the axis represents a multiplying factor rather than a fixed increment, which allows us to see the full distribution without the large values compressing everything else.

ggplot(nyc %>% filter(resarea > 0), aes(x = resarea)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "darkorange", color = "white", alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_x_log10(labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Residential Area (Log Scale)",
       x = "Residential Area (sq ft)", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(nyc, aes(y = resarea)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "darkorange", color = "darkorange", alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Residential Area",
       y = "Residential Area (sq ft)") +
  theme_minimal()

Q1: EDA Part 2 Missing Value & Outlier Handling

The 188 rows missing both residential and commercial area are removed rather than imputed. Imputing these would create imbalance and give residential area an unfair advantage in later model comparisons. Missing floor values are imputed to the median.

Outliers are not treated as data errors NYCs real estate market genuinely produces extreme values. However, properties beyond 3 standard deviations are removed to keep the analysis focused on typical NYC properties and reduce undue influence on regression results.

# Remove rows missing both area variables
nyc <- nyc %>%
  filter(!is.na(resarea) & !is.na(comarea))

# Impute number of floors to median
nyc$numfloors[is.na(nyc$numfloors)] <- median(nyc$numfloors, na.rm = TRUE)
summary(nyc$numfloors)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.000   2.000   2.000   4.233   4.000  54.000
# Calculate z-scores for area variables
nyc <- nyc %>%
  mutate(z_resarea = abs((resarea - mean(resarea)) / sd(resarea)),
         z_comarea = abs((comarea - mean(comarea)) / sd(comarea)),
         z_lotarea = abs((lotarea - mean(lotarea)) / sd(lotarea)))

# Check how many outliers per variable
sum(nyc$z_resarea > 3)
## [1] 415
sum(nyc$z_comarea > 3)
## [1] 212
sum(nyc$z_lotarea > 3)
## [1] 223
# Remove outliers
nyc <- nyc %>%
  filter(z_resarea <= 3,
         z_comarea <= 3,
         z_lotarea <= 3)

Q1: Correlation Matrix

cor_data <- nyc %>%
  dplyr::select(sale_price, resarea, comarea, lotarea, numfloors) %>%
  na.omit()

cor_matrix <- cor(cor_data)
print(cor_matrix)
##              sale_price    resarea    comarea    lotarea    numfloors
## sale_price  1.000000000 -0.1077970 0.03505761 -0.1302605 -0.006565251
## resarea    -0.107796975  1.0000000 0.39617247  0.6130455  0.740085040
## comarea     0.035057607  0.3961725 1.00000000  0.1240777  0.470541061
## lotarea    -0.130260515  0.6130455 0.12407772  1.0000000  0.178399507
## numfloors  -0.006565251  0.7400850 0.47054106  0.1783995  1.000000000
corrplot(cor_matrix, method = "circle", type = "upper",
         tl.col = "black", tl.srt = 45)

Among typical NYC properties (outliers >3 SD removed), a weak negative correlation exists between residential area and sale price (r = -0.14). This reflects NYCs unique market where smaller properties in premium locations command higher prices than larger properties in less central areas. Commercial area has a very weak positive correlation with sale price, likely because commercial properties tend to be larger to accommodate more workers.

  plot_annotation(title = "Sale Price Relationships with Key Variables")

Residential area shows a slight negative correlation with sale price smaller properties in premium NYC locations tend to sell for more. Commercial area has a weak positive correlation. Both lot area and number of floors show minimal linear relationships with price.

Q1: Simple Regression Best Subsets Selection

= 0.05

best_fit <- regsubsets(sale_price ~ resarea + comarea + lotarea + numfloors,
                       data = nyc, nbest = 2)

subsTable <- function(obj, scale) {
  x <- summary(best_fit)
  m <- cbind(round(x[[scale]], 3), x$which[, -1])
  colnames(m)[1] <- scale
  m[order(m[, 1]), ]
}

Q2: Chi-Squared Independence Test

H: Land use and borough are independent H: Land use and borough are dependent = 0.05

bor_land_table2 <- xtabs(count ~ landuse + borough_y, data = bor_land_table)
bor_land_table2 <- bor_land_table2[rownames(bor_land_table2) != "NA",
                                    colnames(bor_land_table2) != "NA"]

# Build matrix manually
r1  <- c(4876, 1806, 117,  8193, 3544)
r2  <- c(2312,  608, 599,  1881,  106)
r3  <- c(1205,  686, 2809, 1869,   45)
r4  <- c(908,   107, 225,   414,   68)
r5  <- c(231,    59,  82,   210,  106)
r6  <- c(151,    19,   7,   112,   14)
r7  <- c(31,     16,   2,    59,   31)
r8  <- c(90,     31,  33,    44,    7)
r9  <- c(0,       0,   0,     1,    0)
r10 <- c(31,      9,   7,    16,    4)
r11 <- c(0,       0,   2,     0,    0)

bor_land_matrix <- matrix(c(r1, r2, r3, r4, r5, r6, r7, r8, r9, r10, r11),
                           nrow = 11, byrow = TRUE)
colnames(bor_land_matrix) <- c("BK", "BX", "MN", "QN", "SI")

# Degrees of freedom and critical value
df <- (nrow(bor_land_table2) - 1) * (ncol(bor_land_table2) - 1)
cv <- qchisq(0.95, df)
cat("Degrees of freedom:", df, "\nCritical value:", round(cv, 2), "\n")
## Degrees of freedom: 40 
## Critical value: 55.76
# Chi-squared test
chi_sq_test <- chisq.test(bor_land_matrix)
print(chi_sq_test)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  bor_land_matrix
## X-squared = 11220, df = 40, p-value < 2.2e-16

The chi-squared statistic of 11,220.39 far exceeds the critical value of 55.76 (df = 40, = 0.05). We reject the null hypothesis land use and borough are dependent. The distribution of land use types differs significantly across NYC boroughs.

Q4: Multiple Linear Regression Stepwise Selection

set.seed(123)

# 70/30 train/test split
train_index <- createDataPartition(nyc$sale_price, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
caret_train <- nyc[train_index, ]
caret_test  <- nyc[-train_index, ]

# Full model with area and location variables
full_model_location <- lm(sale_price ~ resarea + comarea + lotarea + numfloors +
                            borough_y + factor(landuse),
                          data = caret_train)
summary(full_model_location)

stepwise_location <- stepAIC(full_model_location, direction = "both", trace = FALSE)

## Multiple R-squared:  0.09834,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.09769 
## F-statistic: 151.6 on 17 and 23631 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
# Predictions on test set
preds_test_location <- predict(stepwise_location, newdata = caret_test)
valid_predictions <- !is.na(preds_test_location)
preds_test_clean  <- preds_test_location[valid_predictions]

rmse_location <- sqrt(mean((caret_test$sale_price - preds_test_location)^2, na.rm = TRUE))
r2_location   <- summary(stepwise_location)$adj.r.squared

# Test R-squared
ss_res   <- sum((caret_test$sale_price[valid_predictions] - preds_test_clean)^2)
ss_tot   <- sum((caret_test$sale_price[valid_predictions] - mean(caret_test$sale_price[valid_predictions]))^2)
test_r2  <- 1 - (ss_res / ss_tot)

cat("Test R:", round(test_r2, 4), "\n")
## Test R: 0.0945
cat("=== Model Comparison ===\n")
## === Model Comparison ===
cat("Area-only model:\n")
## Area-only model:
cat("  Adjusted R: 0.0235 (2.35%)\n\n")
##   Adjusted R: 0.0235 (2.35%)
cat("Stepwise with Borough + Land Use:\n")
## Stepwise with Borough + Land Use:
cat("  Test RMSE:", round(rmse_location, 2), "\n")
##   Test RMSE: 1194841
cat("  Adjusted R:", round(r2_location, 4), "\n\n")
##   Adjusted R: 0.0977
cat("Improvement:\n")
## Improvement:
cat("  R increase:", round(r2_location - 0.0235, 4), "\n")
##   R increase: 0.0742
cat("  Observations used:", sum(valid_predictions), "out of", length(preds_test_location), "\n")
##   Observations used: 10134 out of 10135

Adding borough and land use to a stepwise regression model substantially improves prediction of NYC property sale prices. Adjusted R increased from 2.35% (area-only) to 9.77% (area + location), a 7.42 percentage point improvement. Test RMSE decreased from $1,206,561 to $1,194,841. Notably, stepwise selection dropped residential area from the final model, indicating its predictive power is absorbed by location factors. This confirms that where a property is located matters far more than how big it is in the NYC real estate market.
